Vheadline
p2
VCultural extravaganza
p3
sVnews
p4
VAs soon as the blistering heat came to an end, there has been a spurt in cultural programmes in Vijayawada. The two-day music and dance fete was conducted at Gokaraju Laila Gangaraju Kala Vedika in the premises of the Government College of Music and \u000aDance, a popular venue for cultural programmes.The college, with joint sponsorship of Andhra Nataka Kala Samithi, conducted the programmes. The programme began with a group singing of Annamacharya keertanas by the college students, directed well by Manda Krishna Mohan, vocal lecturer in the college. Some of the highlights wereOkaparikokapari,Chakkani Talliki,Muddugare Yasoda,Jagadapu ChanavulaandEkkadi Manusha Janmambu. Singers Kranti, Vishnu Padmini, Vaishnavi, Aruna, Archana, Mahija, Vijayalakshmi and Hymavathi did justice by singing in fine unision and sruti sudham. Instrumental support was provided by Hemalata (violin), Vijayakumar (mridangam) and Jashua (tabla).The main item of the evening was a sumptuous vocal concert by Kari Kurmanadh, vocal lecturer in the Government Music College, Rajahmundry. Sporting a deep and vibrant voice and sticking to pure traditional style, Kurmanadh started with a composition of Ganapathi Satchidananda Swamy&#8217;sJaya Jaya Ganapathiin Hamsadhvani and finished it with fine kalpana swaras.He followed it withEmani Pogaduduraof Thyagaraja in Veeravasantam, a rare janya raga. Kurmanadh showed a fine sense of raga bhava in the alapana of khamas in which he rendered the keertanaSantana Gopalam. Another major item in his concert wasPankaja Lochanain Kalyani which was preceded by fine raga delineation. The main piece in Kurmanadh&#8217;s concert wasRamakadhasudhaof Thyagaraja in Madhyamavathi. The singer exhibited expertise in the raga delineation and kalpana swaras. The keertana was rendered with clarity of sahitya and rich bhava. The swara kalpana was followed by a sparkling tani by mridangam player I. Pinakapani of Nellore who is a staffer of Government Music College, Nellore. B.V. Durga Bhavani, a staff artiste of Vijayawada Akashvani gave melodious support on the violin and her versions of Kalyani and Madhyamavathi were attractive. Kurmanadh closed his concert with an Annamacharya keertanaKarunanidhimin Kannada Gowla.P. S.
